{{location map+ |Armenia |float=right |width=250 |caption=Location of UNESCO World Heritage sites within Armenia |places= {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=41.093889 |long=44.711944 |label=[[Haghpat Monastery|Haghpat]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=41.087222 |long=44.666111 |label=[[Sanahin Monastery|Sanahin]]|position=left}} {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=40.172778 |long=44.2925 |label=[[Vagharshapat, Armenia|Echmiadzin]]|position=left}} {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=40.1625 |long=44.403333 |label=[[Zvartnots Cathedral|Zvartnots]]|position=top}} {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=40.156111|long=44.798889 |label=[[Geghard]]|position=right}} {{location map~ |Armenia |lat=40.111853 |long=44.736210 |label=[[Azat River|Azat valley]]|position=bottom}} }}
The [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) [[World Heritage site]]s are places of importance to [[cultural heritage|cultural]] or [[natural heritage]] as described in the UNESCO World Heritage Convention, established in 1972.<ref name="convention">{{cite web|title=The World Heritage Convention|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/convention/|website=UNESCO|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401145714/http://whc.unesco.org/en/convention/|archivedate=1 April 2016}}</ref> Following the [[breakup of Soviet Union]], [[Armenia]] succeeded the convention on 5 September 1993.<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/am</ref>
{{As of|2018}}, Armenia has three sites on the list, with additional four on the tentative list (the official list of sites that may be considered for future submission). All three sites on the list are listed as cultural sites, as determined by the organization's [[World Heritage site#Selection criteria|selection criteria]].<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/am</ref> __TOC__ {{clear}} == World Heritage sites == UNESCO lists sites under [[World Heritage site#Selection criteria|ten criteria]]; each entry must meet at least one of the criteria. Criteria i through vi are cultural, whereas vii through x are natural.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/criteria/|title=UNESCO World Heritage Centre – The Criteria for Selection|publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre|accessdate=17 August 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612152223/http://whc.unesco.org/en/criteria/|archive-date=12 June 2016|dead-url=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
{|class="wikitable plainrowheaders" |- ! style="width:180px;" scope="col"| Site ! class="unsortable" style="width:150px;" scope="col"| Image ! style="width:100px;" scope="col"| Location ! style="width:50px;" scope="col"| Year listed ! style="width:80px;" scope="col" data-sort-type="number"| {{Abbr|UNESCO data|UNESCO reference number and criteria}} ! scope="col" class="unsortable" | Description |- | Monasteries of [[Haghpat Monastery|Haghpat]] and [[Sanahin Monastery|Sanahin]] | [[File:Armenia Haghbat.jpg|150px]][[File:Sanahin-external-view.jpg|150px]] | Villages of Haghpat and Sanahin, Lori Region | 1996 | 777; ii, iv (cultural) | These two monasteries in the Tumanian region from the period of prosperity during the Kiurikian dynasty (10th to 13th century) were important centres of learning. Sanahin was renowned for its school of illuminators and calligraphers. The two monastic complexes represent the highest flowering of Armenian religious architecture, whose unique style developed from a blending of elements of Byzantine ecclesiastical architecture and the traditional vernacular architecture of the Caucasian region.<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/777</ref> |- | Cathedral and Churches of [[Vagharshapat, Armenia|Echmiatsin]] and the Archaeological Site of [[Zvartnots Cathedral|Zvartnots]] | [[File:Etchmiadzin cathedral.jpg|150 px]][[File:Zvartnots cathedral ruins.jpg|150 px]] | Armavir Region | 2000 | 1011; ii, iii (cultural) | The cathedral and churches of Echmiatsin and the archaeological remains at Zvartnots graphically illustrate the evolution and development of the Armenian central-domed cross-hall type of church, which exerted a profound influence on architectural and artistic development in the region.<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1011</ref> |- | Monastery of [[Geghard]] and the Upper [[Azat River|Azat Valley]] | [[File:Geghard entrance-IMG 2525.JPG|150px]][[File:Ազատի ջրամբար.JPG|150px]] | Kotayk Region, near the village of Goght | 2000 | 960; ii (cultural) | The monastery of Geghard contains a number of churches and tombs, most of them cut into the rock, which illustrate the very peak of Armenian medieval architecture. The complex of medieval buildings is set into a landscape of great natural beauty, surrounded by towering cliffs at the entrance to the Azat Valley.<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/960</ref> |}
