{{Infobox mountain | name = Møllehøj | photo = Mollehøj from Ejer Bavnehøj.JPG | photo_caption = Møllehøj seen from the tower on Ejer Bavnehøj, the highest point is obscured by the farm buildings | photo_size = | elevation_m = 170.86 | elevation_ref = | prominence_m = 161 | prominence_ref = <ref>{{cite peakbagger|pid=28239|name=Møllehøj, Denmark|accessdate=2014-08-02}}</ref> | listing = [[List of countries by highest point|Country high point]] | map = Denmark | map_caption = Location of Møllehøj in Denmark | map_size = 275 | label_position = left | location = [[Skanderborg municipality]], [[Denmark]] | range = | coordinates = {{coord|55|58|37.88|N|9|49|34.42|E|type:mountain_region:DK_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | range_coordinates = | coordinates_ref = | topo = | first_ascent = | easiest_route = }}
'''Møllehøj''' is the highest ''natural'' point<ref>{{Cite book | title = Europe's High Points: Getting to the top in 50 countries | author = Rachel Crolla, Carl McKeating | publisher = Cicerone Press Limited | year = 2014 | chapter = 10 Denmark - Møllehøj}}</ref><ref group="Note">For comparison, the tallest man-made structure in Denmark is the [[List of tallest structures in Denmark|Tommerup Transmitter]], which stands 321m or 1045ft high.</ref> in [[Denmark]] at {{Convert|170.86|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}.
== Geography == [[Image:Mollehøj millstone.JPG|thumb|left|The millstone marking the top of Møllehøj]] Møllehøj is in the Ejerbjerge hills in [[Skanderborg municipality]], very close to [[Ejer Bavnehøj]]. The summit is marked with a [[millstone]], a remnant of Ejer [[windmill|mill]] which was situated on the hill from 1838 to 1917. The mill had eight sides and had an onion-shaped roof.
New measurements made in February 2005 showed that Møllehøj was higher than both [[Yding Skovhøj]] (172.66&nbsp;m including a [[Bronze Age]] [[burial mound]] on its summit, 170.77&nbsp;m without) in [[Horsens municipality]] or Ejer Bavnehøj which had both been thought higher. These two high points' natural heights are however respectively 9 and 51&nbsp;cm lower than Møllehøj. It was officially recognised as Denmark's highest point in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://gst.dk/nyheder/nyhedsarkiv/2005/feb/hoejste-punkt/ |title = Nyt højeste punkt i Danmark | website= gst.dk | publisher=Geodatastyrelsen (Danish Geodata Agency - Danish Ministry of Energy, Utilities and Climate) |access-date= 30 December 2017}}</ref>
{{clear|left}}
==See also== * [[Himmelbjerget]], which was thought to be the highest point of Denmark until 1847
