'''Nepal Standard Time''' ('''NPT''') is the [[time zone]] for [[Nepal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=A Brief Legal History of Time: Part One of Two|url=http://www.bna.com/part-one-two-n57982065980/|website=www.bna.com}}</ref> With a time offset from [[Coordinated Universal Time]] (UTC) of [[UTC+05:45|+5:45]] all over Nepal,<ref name=nep>{{cite web|last=Gurung|first=Trishna|title=15 minutes of fame|url=http://www.nepalitimes.com.np/issue/155/Heritage/10013#.UERE7I5RofE|publisher=Nepali Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725100005/http://www.nepalitimes.com.np/issue/155/Heritage/10013|archivedate=25 Jul 2011|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> it is one of only three time zones with a 45-minute offset from UTC. (The others are [[Chatham Island Standard Time]], with an offset of [[UTC+12:45]], and the unofficial [[Time in Australia|Australian Central Western Time]], with an offset of [[UTC+08:45]].)<ref>[https://www.timeanddate.com/time/time-zones-interesting.html timeanddate.com, Half Hour and 45-Minute Time Zones]</ref>
NPT is an approximation of [[Kathmandu]] [[local mean time|mean time]], which is 5:41:16 ahead of [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]. The standard meridian passes through the peak of [[Gaurishankar]] mountain about 100 km east of Kathmandu.<ref name=nep>{{cite web|last=Gurung|first=Trishna|title=15 minutes of fame|url=http://www.nepalitimes.com.np/issue/155/Heritage/10013#.UERE7I5RofE|publisher=Nepali Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725100005/http://www.nepalitimes.com.np/issue/155/Heritage/10013|archivedate=25 Jul 2011|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref>
